SIMPLE: satellite
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Satellite
<hw>Sat"el*lite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>satelles</ets>, <ets>-itis</ets>, an attendant.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>An attendant attached to a prince or other powerful person; hence,
an obsequious dependent.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>satellites</xex> of
power.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>I. Disraeli.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>A secondary planet which
revolves about another planet; <as>as, the moon is a <ex>satellite</ex>
of the earth</as>. See <cref>Solar system</cref>, under
<er>Solar</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Satellite moth</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
handsome European noctuid moth (<spn>Scopelosoma
satellitia</spn>).</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satellite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Satellite
<hw>Sat"el*lite</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Situated
near; accompanying; <as>as, the <ex>satellite</ex> veins, those which
accompany the arteries</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satellitious</ent>⟦br⟧
